Generics allow you to write type-safe code that works with any type.

```java
// Generic method
public <T> T getFirst(List<T> list) {
    return list.get(0);
}

// Generic class
public class Box<T> {
    private T value;
    public Box(T v) { value = v; }
    public T get() { return value; }
}

Box<Integer> intBox = new Box<>(42);
Box<String>  strBox = new Box<>("hello");
```

- `<T>` — type parameter placeholder
- Checked at compile time — no `ClassCastException` at runtime
- The diamond operator `<>` infers the type (Java 7+)
- Generics are erased at runtime (type erasure)
